*Please note that the question remains why your internal methods use the interface and the method exposed publicly uses a concrete class. Usually it&#39;s the other way around. If at all possible I suggest changing the return type of `findAllPaginatedAndSorted` to `List&lt;? extends IDto&gt;`.*

---

You cannot cast from `List&lt;? extends IDto&gt;` to `List&lt;FollowingResponseDto&gt;` because the former can contain other types that implement `IDto`, not just `FollowingResponseDto`.

Imagine the following scenario:

    interface I {}
    class A implements I {}
    class B implements I {}

    List&lt;I&gt; interfaceList = ...;
    interfaceList.add(new A());
    interfaceList.add(new B());
    List&lt;A&gt; aList = interfaceList;  // error! interfaceList contains a B, and a B is not allowed in a list of As

Now you might argue that there is no `B` in your scenario and that the `List&lt;? extends IDto&gt;` contains only instances of `FollowingResponseDto`. But your compiler doesn&#39;t know that and also there is no guarantee that this wouldn&#39;t change anytime in the future.

To fix this, you need to do the conversion yourself. Either do an evil in-between cast into `List&lt;?&gt;` or create a new `List&lt;FollowingResponseDto&gt;` and add each element from the `List&lt;? extends IDto&gt;` individually:

evil:

    return (List&lt;FollowingResponseDto&gt;)(List&lt;?&gt;)findPaginatedAndSortedInternal(...);

not evil:

    var idtoList = findPaginatedAndSortedInternal(...);
    var followingResponseDtoList = new ArrayList&lt;FollowingResponseDto&gt;();
    for (var idto : idtoList) {
        if (idto instanceof FollowingResponseDto)
            followingResponseDtoList.add((FollowingResponseDto)idto);
    }
    return followingResponseDtoList;

